ansferred to the irreducible representations of G containing a given simple type. This leads to a complete classification of the irreduc-ible smooth representations of G, including an explicit description of the supercuspidal representations as induced representations. A special feature of this work is its virtually complete reliance on algebraic methods of a ring-theoretic kind. A full and accessible account of these methods is given here.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aNonstandard mathematical analysis. 0aRepresentations of groups. 7aMATHEMATICS / Algebra / Linear.2bisacsh  aAbelian group.  aAbuse of notation.  aAdditive group.  aAffine Hecke algebra.  aAlgebra homomorphism.  aApproximation.  aAutomorphism.  aBijection.  aBlock matrix.  aCalculation.  aCardinality.  aClassical group.  aComputation.  aConjecture.  aConjugacy class.  aContradiction.  aCorollary.  aCoset.  aCritical exponent.  aDiagonal matrix.  aDimension (vector space).  aDimension.  aDiscrete series representation.  aDiscrete valuation ring.  aDivisor.  aEigenvalues and eigenvectors.  aEquivalence class.  aExact sequence.  aExactness.  aExistential quantification.  aExplicit formula.  aExplicit formulae (L-function).  aField extension.  aFinite group.  aFunctor.  aGauss sum.  aGeneral linear group.  aGroup theory.  aHaar measure.  aHarmonic analysis.  aHecke algebra.  aHomomorphism.  aIdentity matrix.  aInduced representation.  aInteger.  aIrreducible representation.  aIsomorphism class.  aIwahori subgroup.  aJordan normal form.  aLevi decomposition.  aLocal Langlands conjectures.  aLocal field.  aLocally compact group.  aMathematics.  aMatrix coefficient.  aMaximal compact subgroup.  aMaximal ideal.  aMultiset.  aNormal subgroup